Why We Need Them
There are cases where you want to store documents with varying data structures/schemas in a single collection, but they all share the same root document schema. That’s exactly when you use discriminators in Mongoose, they let you write sub-schemas under a parent/root schema.
This avoids the hassle of cramming every possible field into one giant UserSchema, which quickly becomes hard to read and maintain. Instead, each variant gets its own clean, focused schema, while still living in the same collection as the root schema.
The Problem: One Schema, Trying to Be Everything
Say you need one User collection to support both employees and managers. Without discriminators, you'd typically end up cramming every field from every variant into a single schema, marking most of them optional:
const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
email: {
type: String,
required: true,
unique: true
},
name: {
type: String,
required: true
},
accountType: {
type: String,
enum: ['EMPLOYEE', 'MANAGER'],
required: true
}// Only relevant if accountType === 'EMPLOYEE'
employeeId: {
type: String,
unique: true,
sparse: true
},
reportingManager: {
type: mongoose.Types.ObjectId,
ref: "User"
},// Only relevant if accountType === 'MANAGER'
managerId: {
type: String,
unique: true,
sparse: true
},
reportingEmployees: [
{
type: mongoose.Types.ObjectId,
ref: "User"
}
]
});const User = mongoose.model('User', UserSchema);A few problems with this:

• No real validation boundary. Nothing stops you from creating a document with accountType: 'EMPLOYEE' that also has managerId and reportingEmployees filled in. You'd have to hand-write custom validators to enforce "these fields only make sense together."

• Readability suffers as variants grow. Add a third or fourth account type, and this schema balloons into a long list of loosely-related optional fields, with comments doing the work that separate schemas would do automatically.

• unique doesn't play well with optional fields. Fields like employeeId need sparse: true so the unique index doesn't choke on the many documents where it's undefined.

• No dedicated model per type. You lose the convenience of calling Employee.find() or Manager.create() directly, every query has to manually filter on accountType yourself.
Here’s the same thing built with discriminators instead, the shared fields stay in one root schema, and each variant’s fields live in their own, isolated schema:
The Example (Default discriminatorKey)
Here’s the same setup, built with discriminators. If you don’t pass a discriminatorKey option at all, Mongoose falls back to its own default field for tagging documents: __t.
const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
email: {
type: String,
required: true,
unique: true
},
name: {
type: String,
required: true
}
});const EmployeeSchema = UserSchema.discriminator('EMPLOYEE', new mongoose.Schema({
employeeId: {
type: String,
required: true,
unique: true
},
reportingManager: {
type: mongoose.Types.ObjectId,
ref: "User"
}
}));const ManagerSchema = UserSchema.discriminator('MANAGER', new mongoose.Schema({
managerId: {
type: String,
required: true,
unique: true
},
reportingEmployees: [
{
type: mongoose.Types.ObjectId,
ref: "User"
}
]
}));
const User = mongoose.model('User', UserSchema);
const Employee = User.discriminators['EMPLOYEE'];
const Manager = User.discriminators['MANAGER'];
module.exports = { User, Employee, Manager };Here, User is the root schema, while Employee and Manager are discriminators built on top of it. No discriminatorKey option was passed, so Mongoose tags each document under __t automatically.
What the Documents Look Like (Default __t Key)
A plain User document
await User.create({
email: "johndoe@example.com",
name: "John Doe"
});{
"_id": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d1",
"email": "johndoe@example.com",
"name": "John Doe",
"__v": 0
}No __t field is present, this is just a base document, nothing extra attached.
An Employee document
await Employee.create({
email: "janedoe@example.com",
name: "Jane Doe",
employeeId: "EMP-042",
reportingManager: "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d3"
});{
"_id": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d2",
"__t": "EMPLOYEE",
"email": "janedoe@example.com",
"name": "Jane Doe",
"employeeId": "EMP-042",
"reportingManager": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d3",
"__v": 0
}Notice the __t: "EMPLOYEE" field, this is the default discriminator key that tags the document. Along with the base email and name fields, it also carries employeeId and reportingManager, which only exist on the Employee schema.
A Manager document
await Manager.create({
email: "jackdoe@example.com",
name: "Jack Doe",
managerId: "MGR-007",
reportingEmployees: ["64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d2"]
});{
"_id": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d3",
"__t": "MANAGER",
"email": "jackdoe@example.com",
"name": "Jack Doe",
"managerId": "MGR-007",
"reportingEmployees": ["64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d2"],
"__v": 0
}Same base fields, but this time tagged __t: "MANAGER", and carrying managerId and reportingEmployees instead.
Passing a Custom discriminatorKey
__t works fine, but it's not the most readable field name to see sitting in your documents. Mongoose lets you override it by passing a discriminatorKey option to the root schema:
const UserSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
email: {
type: String,
required: true,
unique: true
},
name: {
type: String,
required: true
}
}, {
discriminatorKey: 'accountType'
});Everything else about EmployeeSchema, ManagerSchema, and the model setup stays exactly the same as before. The only difference is the field name used for tagging. The resulting documents now look like this:
{
"_id": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d2",
"accountType": "EMPLOYEE",
"email": "janedoe@example.com",
"name": "Jane Doe",
"employeeId": "EMP-042",
"reportingManager": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d3",
"__v": 0
}{
"_id": "64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d3",
"accountType": "MANAGER",
"email": "jackdoe@example.com",
"name": "Jack Doe",
"managerId": "MGR-007",
"reportingEmployees": ["64f1a2b3c4d5e6f7a8b9c0d2"],
"__v": 0
}Same idea as __t, just a friendlier, self-documenting field name doing the tagging.
One Collection, Varying Structures
All three documents above, the plain User, the Employee, and the Manager , are stored in the same MongoDB collection (users). If you ran db.users.find() directly in the Mongo shell, you'd see all of them side by side, each with a different shape depending on whether (and how) they're tagged.
This is the core benefit: one collection, one set of shared fields, but each discriminator can carry its own extra fields without polluting the others.
Querying Across Root and Discriminators
Since Employee and Manager are both built on top of User, all three point to the same underlying collection when querying:
await User.find();
// Returns ALL documents in the users collection: plain Users,
// Employees, and Managers alike, mixed together.await Employee.find();
// Returns ONLY documents where accountType === 'EMPLOYEE'
// Mongoose automatically adds this filter behind the scenes,
// and gives back documents with Employee-specific fields intact.await Manager.find();
// Returns ONLY documents where accountType === 'MANAGER'
// Same idea - filtered and shaped according to the Manager schema.Each model (User, Employee, Manager) talks to the exact same users collection under the hood, the only difference is how much filtering and shaping Mongoose applies before handing you the result.
What Mongoose Is Actually Doing Under the Hood
Discriminators aren’t a special MongoDB feature, MongoDB has no idea what a “discriminator” is. It’s purely a Mongoose-level trick, and it comes down to two things:

• Schema merging. When you call UserSchema.discriminator('EMPLOYEE', EmployeeSchema), Mongoose takes the fields from EmployeeSchema and merges them on top of a clone of UserSchema. The resulting model's schema is effectively { ...UserSchema.fields, ...EmployeeSchema.fields }, plus the discriminator key field, added automatically as an enum-constrained string (its allowed values are the discriminator names you've registered, e.g. EMPLOYEE, MANAGER).

• Query filter injection. Every discriminator model shares the exact same underlying collection as the root model (they literally point at the same db.collection). When you call Employee.find() or Employee.create(), Mongoose silently adds { accountType: 'EMPLOYEE' } (or { __t: 'EMPLOYEE' }) to your filter/insert behind the scenes. That's the entire mechanism, there's no separate storage, no join, no magic at the database layer. It's just an automatically-applied WHERE clause plus a merged schema.
This is also why the discriminator key ends up saved on every document: it’s not metadata Mongoose tracks separately, it’s a real field in the collection that the discriminator models use to filter themselves back out later.
Conclusion
Discriminators are worth reaching for whenever you have multiple entity types that share a common core but diverge in a few specific fields, like different account types, different content types in a CMS, or different notification types. Instead of one bloated schema riddled with optional fields, or multiple disconnected collections duplicating the shared fields, discriminators let you:

• Keep shared fields defined once, in one place

• Add type-specific fields only where they’re relevant

• Query either the full set or a specific subtype, with Mongoose handling the filtering automatically
The result is schema code that’s easier to read, easier to extend, and a database structure that stays consistent without giving up flexibility.
